description: The mummy is believed to be a relative of Senmut, an architect who worked during the reign of ancient Egypt’s most powerful female leader, Queen Hatshepsut. Senmut’s final years also remain a mystery.
title: New evidence suggests 'Screaming Woman' mummy died in pain

description: The far-right Alternative for Germany party is leading the polls ahead of state elections. A group called "Grandmas Against the Far-Right" is trying to get German voters to shun the AfD party.
title: 'Grandmas Against the Far-Right' hope to change AfD supporters' minds in Germany

description: American Ryan Crouser has turned the shot put into a science. As he goes for his third Olympic gold in a row, he keeps tweaking ideas of rotation, radius and speed and utilizes computer mechanics.
title: Olympic champ Ryan Crouser goes for gold again with an intricate approach to shot put

description: World record holder Joshua Cheptegei of Uganda looked up to four-time Olympic medalist Kenenisa Bekele as a kid. He just stole the Ethiopian's Olympic record. Grant Fisher won bronze for the U.S.
title: The fastest 10,000m runner still reigns, and U.S. steps onto podium after 12 years

description: Democrats believe they have an opportunity to make inroads with an important voting bloc in swing state Arizona: Latinos.
title: Harris courts Latino voters in Arizona

description: The Olympic Games almost always comes with a substantial financial burden for a host city. But are cost-benefit analysts too simplistic for how we evaluate their impact?
title: The cost of putting on the Olympics is making it harder to find host cities

description: Before any public office, Kamala Harris went to Washington, D.C., to study at Howard University. Jill Louis, class of '87, joined Alpha Kappa Alpha at the same time as Harris.
title: Sorority sister of Kamala Harris remembers her as the 'consummate college student'

description: The U.S. swim team entered Paris confident after a strong showing in national trials. But the American team's stars struggled again on Friday night as swimmers from Australia and France dominated.
title: U.S. swimmers falter again on day seven of Olympics, winning a single silver medal

description: After gaining national attention as one of the "Tennessee Three," state Rep. Gloria Johnson will try to ride Democratic enthusiasm in her run against U.S. Sen. Marsha Blackburn in November.
title: Johnson, one of the so-called Tennessee 3, will face Blackburn in U.S. Senate race

description: NPR’S Ailsa Chang talks with former Israeli diplomat Alon Pinkas, about whether Israel might be provoking an escalation in the Middle East that could drag the U.S. into conflict.
title: Is Israel provoking a regional war in the Middle East?

description: Black farmers got $2 billion in USDA payments to address discrimination in farm loans. For decades, Black farmers and others have argued that they’ve been left behind by the USDA’s lending programs.
title: USDA issues payments to address discrimination against Black farmers

description: The Justice Department has sued TikTok over violating children's privacy. It’s the latest legal trouble for the Chinese-owned video app.
title: DOJ sues TikTok for unlawful data collection from kids

description: At the halfway mark of the Paris Olympics, China is running well ahead of the U.S. and every other country in the gold medals tally. China's success stems from two sports: diving and shooting.
title: Let's talk about China's whopping Olympic gold medal count

description: Former President Donald Trump still can't speak about prosecutors in his New York criminal trial after an appeals court decision denied his attempt to lift the gag order.
title: Trump loses bid to lift New York gag order in response to Harris’ campaigning

description: Federal Judge Tanya Chutkan must decide what to do in the election interference case against former President Donald Trump after the U.S. Supreme Court's immunity ruling.
title: Trump election interference case returns to D.C. after immunity ruling

description: U.S. employers added just 114,000 jobs in July as the unemployment rate rose to 4.3%. The weaker-than-expected report is adding to fears of an economic slowdown.
title: Why a weaker jobs market is sparking recession fears

description: The Dutch team had little margin for error. Heading into Friday's final, they were one point out of first place.
title: Dutch sailors mistakenly stop short of the finish in gold medal race

description: Laotian athlete Silina Pha Aphay had just placed sixth, ending her journey at the Paris Olympics. But her first reaction was to go to her competitor, Lucia Moris of South Sudan, who had fallen.
title: An Olympic sprinter fell during a race. The first person to help was her opponent

description: Former U.K. Prime Minister Gordon Brown says Washington Post CEO Will Lewis told police a "clearly fabricated" account in 2011 to justify destroying emails amid a scandal. Lewis denies wrongdoing.
title: Former UK Prime Minister says Bezos should reconsider 'Washington Post' publisher

description: Olympic organizers are defending the participation of two boxers who failed a gender eligibility test last year. Here's what to know about the key players, conservative outcry and official response.
title: What to know about the gender controversy sweeping Olympic boxing

description: An international sports tribunal in Switzerland rejected an appeal by Canadian figure skaters and confirmed that the bronze medal would go to Russian athletes from the 2022 Beijing Games.
title: Russian figure skaters awarded team bronze despite Valieva doping scandal

description: A jury had awarded $4.7 billion in damages to subscribers after it ruled the NFL violated antitrust laws in distributing out-of-market Sunday afternoon games on a premium subscription service.
title: U.S. judge overturns $4.7 billion 'Sunday Ticket' judgment against the NFL

description: It was the first appearance at an Olympics by the U.S. men's soccer team since 2008. The quarterfinal loss to Morocco is a tough one for the U.S. as the squad exits the Paris Olympics.
title: Bounced out: The U.S. men's soccer team loses Olympic quarterfinal game to Morocco

description: The short documentary is called The Visionary Women of Indonesia. It profiles women ophthalmologists who are addressing the high rate of blindness in their country — and fighting sexism as well.
title: Prize for the eyes: WHO honors film on Indonesia's pioneering women eye docs

description: NPR's Leila Fadel talks with National Security Adviser Jake Sullivan about Washington's role in securing one of the largest prisoner swaps between the U.S., its allies and Russia since the Cold War ended.
title: How the U.S. helped secure the historic prisoner swap with Russia

description: Why have the Paris Olympics brought so many exciting swimming events — but not so many world records? It turns out that the pool's depth is just one possible reason.
title: Is the Paris pool slow and shallow? Experts say it’s not only about depth

description: Writer James Baldwin is remembered by his family, a scholar, a journalist and a playwright on his 100th birthday.
title: Reflections on James Baldwin's magnificent life from those who knew him

description: Americans were welcomed home last night after the largest prisoner exchange between the West and Russia since the end of the Cold War. And, Simone Biles secures her GOAT status at the Olympics.
title: Who are the Americans freed in a Russian prisoner swap? And, Simone Biles is GOAT

description: NPR's Leila Fadel speaks to Alina Polyakova, of the Center for European Policy Analysis, and a friend of Vladimir Kara-Murza, who was recently freed in a Russia-U.S. prisoner swap.
title: Russian opposition figure, Vladimir Kara-Murza, was released in prisoner swap

description:
What’s it feel like waiting to hear if you’re chosen to be the vice presidential nominee? NPR's A Martinez talks to 
Sen.Tim Kaine of Virginia who knows what's it is like.
title: Kamala Harris is expected to pick her running mate in the next few days

description: In this week's StoryCorps, a mother talks with her son about how she overcame her addiction to drugs.
title: A woman addicted to methamphetamine says becoming a mother turned her life around

description: We take a peak behind the curtain at the Olympic Village, inside the cafeteria that's been called the world's largest restaurant.
title: Olympic Village cafeteria serves 40,000 meals a day to the world’s best athletes

description: Activists want the autocratic prime minister to step down.
title: Bangladesh is witnessing the deadliest protests in its history

description: What options does the U.S. have to tamp down tensions in the Middle East? NPR's Leila Fadel speaks with former U.S. Ambassador to Israel Edward Djerejian.
title: The U.S. is being urged to help lower the escalating tensions in the Middle East
